=Text System=

This page documents the text encoding and dialog system used in Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest.

==Overview==

Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest uses a sophisticated text compression system based on:
* '''DTE (Dual Tile Encoding)''' - Common phrases compressed into single bytes
* '''Simple character tables''' - Direct 1:1 character mappings
* '''Control codes''' - Special functions for textbox positioning, character names, etc.
* '''Language variants''' - Each region has customized text tables

==Text Encoding==

The text system loads character tables into VRAM during gameplay:
* '''English versions''': VRAM $6300-$6fff
* '''Other versions''': VRAM $6200-$6fff

Text is stored in ROM using a combination of:
* Literal characters from the simple table ($90-$dd for English)
* DTE compressed phrases ($3d-$7e)
* Control codes for formatting and special functions ($01-$36)
* Space/newline character ($ff)

==DTE Compression==

DTE (Dual Tile Encoding) compresses common letter combinations and words into single bytes, achieving approximately 30% space savings. For example:

* '''Without DTE''': "The crystal is going to help you!" = 39 bytes
* '''With DTE''': Same text using DTE codes = ~27 bytes

See [[Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest/Text/Complex_Text|Complex Text]] for the complete DTE table and compression details.

==Language Variants==

Each regional version has a customized text table optimized for that language:

* '''[[Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest/TBL/English|English]]''' - US and European versions with English DTE phrases
* '''[[Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest/TBL/French|French]]''' - Includes accented characters (é, è, ê, ç, etc.) and French DTE
* '''[[Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest/TBL/German|German]]''' - Includes umlauts (ä, ö, ü) and ß with German DTE
* '''[[Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest/TBL/Japanese|Japanese]]''' - Uses hiragana/katakana instead of DTE compression

==Dialog System==

Dialog uses control codes for:
* '''Textbox positioning''' - Above or below characters ($1a/$1b codes)
* '''Variable text''' - Character names ($1d), item names ($1e), location names ($1f)
* '''Player interaction''' - Wait for button press ($30), display player's name ($35)
* '''Character actions''' - Movement and action sequences ($36)

See [[Final Fantasy: Mystic Quest/Notes/Script_Analysis|Script Analysis]] for dialog examples and encoding patterns.

